{{distinguish|text=[[phylogeny]], the study of relationships between species}} {{Wiktionary|philogyny}}
'''Philogyny''' is fondness, love, or admiration towards [[women]].<ref name="oxford">{{cite web|url=http://www.oxfordreference.com/views/ENTRY.html?entry=t140.e58312|publisher=[[Oxford English Dictionary]]|title=philogynist – The Oxford Dictionary of English (2nd edition revised) – Oxford Reference Online}}</ref><ref name="wordnet">{{cite web|url=http://wordnetweb.princeton.edu/perl/webwn?s=philogyny|title=WordNet|publisher=[[Princeton University]]|accessdate=2009-08-31}}</ref> Its [[antonym]] is ''[[misogyny]]''. Philogyny is not be confused with [[gynephilia]], which is [[sexual attraction]] to women or [[femininity]] (and whose antonym is ''[[gynophobia]]'').
Cicero reports the word could be used in Greek philosophy to denote being overly fond of women, which was considered a disease along with misogyny.<ref name="Deming">A recent critical text with translation is in [https://books.google.com/books?id=u_6a-sMDv6AC&pg=PA221&lpg=PA221&dq=appendix+a+antipater+of+tarsus&source=web&ots=JlCnsyRBGf&sig=7zsKzMVEBnV3tHag9z7E4cWCeLs&hl=en Appendix A] to Will Deming, ''Paul on Marriage and Celibacy: The Hellenistic Background of 1 Corinthians 7'', pp. 221–226.</ref>
Christian Groes-Green has argued that the conceptual content of philogyny must be developed as an alternative to the concept of misogyny. Criticizing [[R.W. Connell]]'s theory of hegemonic masculinities he shows how philogynous masculinities play out among youth in Maputo, Mozambique.<ref>Groes-Green, C. 2012. "Philogynous masculinities: Contextualizing alternative manhood in Mozambique". Men and Masculinities 15(2):91–111. http://jmm.sagepub.com/content/15/2/91</ref>
== Etymology == ''Philogyny'' comes from ''philo-'' (loving) and Greek ''gynē'' (woman). The parallel [[Greek language|Greek]]-based terms with respect to men (males) are [[philandry]] for "fondness towards men" and [[misandry]] for "hatred of men". Parallel terms for humanity generally are [[philanthropy]] and [[misanthropy]].
== See also == * [[Philandry]] * [[Gynophobia]] * [[Gynephilia]] * [[Gynocentrism]]
